# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: afl-asia-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:afl-asia-cup/2023-co-ed-slow-pitch-softball-asia-cup] The **2023 Co-Ed Slow-Pitch Softball Asia Cup** was an international mixed-gender slow-pitch softball tournament held in Pattaya, Thailand.
[src:afl-asia-cup/2023-co-ed-slow-pitch-softball-asia-cup] The tournament was held at the Siam Polo Ground from 24 to 27 May 2023.
[src:afl-asia-cup/2023-co-ed-slow-pitch-softball-asia-cup] The top three teams are supposed to qualify for the 2023 WBSC Coed Slow Pitch Softball World Cup.
[src:afl-asia-cup/2023-co-ed-slow-pitch-softball-asia-cup] The World Cup to be hosted in Guadalajara, Mexico in December 2023, was eventually cancelled in October 2023 due to logistical challenges.
[src:afl-asia-cup/2023-co-ed-slow-pitch-softball-asia-cup] Chinese Taipei is the inaugural champions.
[src:afl-asia-cup/acbs-asian-snooker-championship] The **ACBS Asian Snooker Championship** is the premier non-professional snooker tournament in Asia.
[src:afl-asia-cup/acbs-asian-snooker-championship] The event series is sanctioned by the Asian Confederation of Billiard Sports and started from 1984.
[src:afl-asia-cup/acbs-asian-snooker-championship] ACBS Asian 6 Reds Snooker Championship: Indian Pankaj Advani claimed the 5th edition ACBS Asian 6 Reds Snooker Championship on in Abu Dhabi.
[src:afl-asia-cup/acbs-asian-snooker-championship] 1st Asian Billiards Sport 2016 was held in 24 September - 2 October 2016 - Al Fujairah - UAE.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The **AFC Asian Cup** is the primary association football competition contested by the senior men's national teams of the members of the Asian Football Confederation (AFC), determining the continental champion of Asia.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] It is the second-oldest continental football championship in the world after Copa América.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The winning team becomes the champions of Asia and, until 2015, qualified for the FIFA Confederations Cup.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The Asian Cup was held once every four years from the 1956 AFC Asian Cup in Hong Kong until the 2004 tournament in China.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] That year, since the Summer Olympic Games and the European Football Championship were also scheduled in the same year as the Asian Cup, the AFC decided to move their championship to a less crowded cycle.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] After 2004, the tournament was next held in 2007, when it was co-hosted by four countries in Southeast Asia: Indonesia, Malaysia, Thailand and Vietnam.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Thereafter, it has again been held every four years.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The Asian Cup has generally been dominated by a small number of top teams.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Prominently successful teams include Japan (four times), Iran, Saudi Arabia (three times each), South Korea and Qatar (twice each).
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The other teams which have achieved success are Australia (2015), Iraq (2007) and Kuwait (1980).
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Israel won in 1964 but was later expelled and has since joined UEFA.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Australia joined the Asian confederation in 2007 and hosted the Asian Cup finals in 2015, winning the competition in the final against South Korea.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] From the 2019 tournament forward, the number of teams was expanded from 16 teams to 24 teams, with the qualifying process doubling as part of the FIFA World Cup qualification.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] A pan-Asian competition was first proposed after the end of World War II, but it was not implemented until the 1950s.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Two years after the Asian Football Confederation (AFC) came into being in 1954, the first ever AFC Asian Cup was staged in British Hong Kong with seven of the twelve founding members taking part, making the tournament the second oldest continental competition in the world.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The qualifying process involved the hosts plus the winners of the various zones (Central, Eastern and Western).
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] It was only a four-team tournament, a format that also existed for 1960 and 1964.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Each sub-confederation already hosts their own biennial championship, each with varying degrees of interest.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] South Korea demonstrated its superiority in the early years of the competition as the country won the championship in both 1956 and 1960; this remains as South Korea's best achievements in the tournament.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] After Hong Kong and South Korea hosted the two first editions, Israel was chosen as host of the 1964 AFC Asian Cup.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Using the same format of the two previous editions, this tournament only had four teams and played in one single group to determine the champions.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Israel eventually topped the tournament ahead of India with three wins.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The format was updated to five teams in 1968 before it was expanded to six teams in 1972 and 1976.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The tournament became the preserve of Iran who won three consecutive tournaments in 1968, 1972 and 1976, with Iran hosting the former and the latter.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Iran remains as the only national team in Asia to have won three consecutive Asian Cups.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The 1972 final was notable as it was the first Asian Cup to use the group stage-knockout phase format, which was followed in the subsequent tournaments with some alternation.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Israel was expelled from the AFC in 1972 due to the Arab–Israeli conflict.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] From 1980 to 1988, the number of teams taking part expanded to ten, but West Asian countries continued their domination in the 1980s with Kuwait becoming the first Arab country to win the championship in 1980 held at home soil, beating South Korea 3–0 in the final.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Saudi Arabia, after an initial poor start, began to emerge as the country qualified, then won two consecutive Asian trophies in 1984 and 1988, overcoming both China and South Korea.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Both tournaments were Saudi Arabia's debuts in any major competitions.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Until the 1990s, Japan was mostly a small name in Asian football, and the country only qualified for the 1988 edition, the first time Japan took part in a continental football tournament.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] However, as Japan started to make a concrete move inroad to professional football, the country's fortunes increased.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Japan hosted the 1992 AFC Asian Cup, which was reduced to eight teams and two groups, where it emerged victorious after beating Saudi Arabia, then-defending champions, 1–0, to win the country's first major international honour.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The 1996 AFC Asian Cup saw the tournament expand to twelve teams in its process of professionalization.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Held by the United Arab Emirates, the hosts breached into the final for the first time ever but were unable to win the trophy after losing to Saudi Arabia, who made it into the country's fourth consecutive Asian finals, on penalties.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] It was Saudi Arabia's third Asian title.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The 2000 AFC Asian Cup saw Lebanon take part in its first Asian tournament, and it was Saudi Arabia who again reached the final, but this time, Japan triumphed over Saudi Arabia 1–0 in a final filled with a majority of Saudi supporters.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Japan would go on to retain their Asian trophy four years later, albeit in a more struggling style and a very heated, politically charged final toward hosts China.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The 2004 edition was notable as it expanded to 16 teams, and marked Saudi Arabia's absence from an Asian Cup final for the first time.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] In this tournament, Iraq was crowned as Asian champions despite the ravaging American invasion, overpowering the likes of Australia, South Korea and Saudi Arabia in the process.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Australia (which joined the AFC in 2006), after its poor debut in 2007, rebounded to reach the final in 2011 AFC Asian Cup in Qatar, but lost to Japan after extra-time; the win for Japan meant it became the most decorated team in Asian football with four titles.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Still, the tournament was notable as the first Asian Cup to use the jersey numbers' order from 1 to 23, previously not practised in prior competitions.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Following Australia's successes in the 2011 Asian Cup, the AFC approved the country to host the 2015 AFC Asian Cup.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] At the tournament, Australia managed to clamp down every opponent with only one loss, against eventual finalist South Korea, whom Australia would get a 2–1 final revenge after extra-time; the win officially sealed Southeast Asia's first Asian title as Australia joined the AFF in 2013.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] At the 2019 AFC Asian Cup, video assistant referees were used in the tournament for the first time, and the tournament expanded to 24 teams.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] In addition, a fourth substitution was allowed during extra time.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The tournament, hosted by the United Arab Emirates for the second time, witnessed the rise of Qatar, who conquered its first ever Asian title after beating Japan in the final 3–1.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The tournament was marred by the Qatar diplomatic crisis, due to the UAE's entry ban on Qatari supporters, as well as shoe-throwing in the two teams' semi-final clash.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] At the 2023 AFC Asian Cup, hosts and defending champions Qatar won their second title in a row, winning against Jordan in the final.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The tournament also featured Yoshimi Yamashita as the first woman to referee at the Asian Cup.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The 2027 AFC Asian Cup may be the final time the tournament is held on odd-numbered years, having been so since 2007.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The AFC is considering moving the tournament to even-numbered years, because of a potential revisions to the FIFA International Match Calendar.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Since 1972, the final tournament has been played in two stages: the group stage and the knockout stage.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Since 2019, the Asian Cup final tournament has been contested by 24 teams, having been expanded from the 16-team format that was used from 2004 to 2015.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Each team plays three games in a group of four, with the winners and runners-up from each group advancing to the knockout stage along with four best third-placed teams.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] In the knockout stage, the sixteen teams compete in a single-elimination tournament, beginning with the round of 16 and ending with the final match of the tournament.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] There have been two Asian Cup trophies; the first one used between 1956 and 2015, and the second one in use since 2019.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The first trophy came in the form of a bowl with circular base.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] It was 42 centimetres tall and weighed 15 kilograms.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Until the 2000 tournament, the black base contained plaques engraved with names of every winning country, as well as the edition won.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The trophy was redesigned, adding more silver and reducing the black base to just a thin layer down.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] This base was plaque-free and the winning countries' names were engraved around the base.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] During the draw for the 2019 group stage on 4 May 2018 at the Burj Khalifa in Dubai, an all-new trophy, made by London silversmiths Thomas Lyte, was unveiled.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] It is 78 centimetres tall, 42 centimetres wide, and weighs 15 kilograms of sterling silver.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The trophy is modelled after the lotus flower, a symbolically important aquatic Asian plant.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The five petals of the lotus symbolize the five sub-confederations under the AFC.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The winning countries' names are engraved around the trophy base, which is separable from the trophy's main body.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] First four edition of competition only had four or five teams and played in one single group.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Since 1972, the final tournament has introduced the knockout stage.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Since 2019, no third place play-off has been played; from 2023, losing semi-finalists are ranked by the AFC based on goal difference in the semi-finals.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Despite being the second oldest continental football tournament, the AFC Asian Cup has suffered numerous criticisms.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Criticisms over the inability of the AFC Asian Cup to attract large attendances, political interference, high costs of traveling between AFC member states and different cultures were highlighted over the Asian Cup.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The AFC Asian Cup is marked with numerous instances of political interference.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] One of these was the case of Israel, as the team used to be a member of the AFC but following the Yom Kippur War and increasing hostility from the Arab AFC members, Israel was expelled from the AFC in 1974 and had to compete in the OFC, until being granted UEFA membership in 1990.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Meanwhile, similar cases also exist in other AFC tournaments like the one between Saudi Arabia and Iran.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Following the 2016 attack on the Saudi diplomatic missions in Iran, Saudi Arabia refused to play against Iran and even threatened to withdraw, afterwards blowing over onto international level.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Tensions between the two Koreas during qualification for the 2010 FIFA World Cup led North Korea to withdraw from hosting the South Korean team and refusing to display the South Korean flag and play their national anthem.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] As a result, North Korea's home matches were moved to Shanghai.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Low crowds have also been another problem for the AFC Asian Cup.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] In 2010, Qatar was chosen as the host country for the 2022 FIFA World Cup.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] The country became the first in the Middle East to host the world's biggest sporting event, triumphing over strong competition from the United States and Australia.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] Approximately 5 billion people were involved in the FIFA World Cup Qatar 2022, as they followed tournament content through various platforms and devices in the media universe.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] On 10 February 2024, the AFC announced that the tournament in Qatar had surpassed the previous total attendance record of 1.04 million set during the 2004 tournament in China, with a new record of 1.06 million.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-asian-cup] This achievement was reached prior to the quarter-final stage.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-beach-soccer-asian-cup] The **AFC Beach Soccer Asian Cup** is the main championship for beach soccer in Asia, contested between the senior men's national teams of the members of the Asian Football Confederation (AFC).
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-beach-soccer-asian-cup] It is the sport's version of the better known AFC Asian Cup in association football.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-beach-soccer-asian-cup] The winners of the championship are crowned continental champions; the tournament also acts as the qualification route for Asian nations to the upcoming edition of the FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-beach-soccer-asian-cup] Coinciding with the annual staging of the World Cup, the competition took place yearly until 2009; the World Cup then became biennial, and as its supplementary qualification event, the championship followed suit.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-beach-soccer-asian-cup] During this time it also became informally known by the misnomer, the *AFC Beach Soccer Championship*.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-beach-soccer-asian-cup] In 2015, the Asia's governing body for football, the AFC adopted the competition and branded it using its informal title in an official capacity; they jointly organised that year's edition with BSWW.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-beach-soccer-asian-cup] Since 2017, the AFC have been sole organisers.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-beach-soccer-asian-cup] For 2021, the competition was renamed as the *AFC Beach Soccer Asian Cup*, bringing it in line with the naming of other AFC senior national tournaments.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-beach-soccer-asian-cup] For all tournaments, the top three teams qualified for the FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup (except for 2009, when only the top two teams qualified as one of the AFC spots was automatically given to the World Cup hosts, United Arab Emirates).
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-beach-soccer-asian-cup] Despite being hosts and defending champions, the United Arab Emirates did not participate in the championship as they had already qualified automatically for the 2009 World Cup as its host nation.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-beach-soccer-asian-cup] Since 2017, the competition's *Technical Study Group* have produced a post-tournament report including a dream and reserve "team of the tournament".
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-beach-soccer-asian-cup] The following is a performance timeline of the teams who have appeared in the AFC Beach Soccer Championship and how many appearances they each have made.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-beach-soccer-asian-cup] The following is a performance timeline of the AFC teams who have appeared in the Beach Soccer World Cup since being sanctioned by FIFA in 2005.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-futsal-asian-cup] The **AFC Futsal Asian Cup**, previously the **AFC Futsal Championship**, is the premier international futsal competition for the Asian Football Confederation (AFC) national teams.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-futsal-asian-cup] It was first held in 1999 and was played annually until 2008; since then it has been played biennially.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-futsal-asian-cup] From 2021, the tournament was rebranded from the **AFC Futsal Championship** to the **AFC Futsal Asian Cup**.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-futsal-asian-cup] The competition in a year divisible by four from 2000 to 2028 also serves as the qualification for the FIFA Futsal World Cup (a standalone qualifier for the World Cup will be held starting from the 2032 edition onwards).
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-futsal-asian-cup] There are 47 countries and territories that are permitted to compete for qualification into the tournament.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-futsal-asian-cup] Iran and Japan are the dominant nations being the only two nations to have won the tournament, and Iran is the only nation to have never finished outside the top three.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-futsal-asian-cup] Iran, champions of 14 of the 18 editions of the competition, won 7 straight editions before their streak was broken by Japan.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-futsal-asian-cup] Iran are the current reigning champions, having won the tournament in 2026.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-futsal-asian-cup] The following twelve teams which are current AFC members have never qualified for the AFC Futsal Asian Cup.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] The **AFC Women's Asian Cup** (formerly known as the **AFC Women's Championship**) is a quadrennial competition in women's football for national teams which belong to the Asian Football Confederation (AFC).
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] It is the oldest women's international football competition and premier women's football competition in the AFC region for national teams.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] The competition is also known as the **Asian Women's Football Championship** and the **Asian Women's Championship**.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] 21 tournaments have been held, with the current champions being Japan.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] Most competitions between 1991 and 2026 also served as the Asian qualifying tournament for the FIFA Women's World Cup.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] The competition was set up by the Asian Ladies Football Confederation (ALFC), a part of the AFC responsible for women's football.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] The first competition was held in 1975 and was held every two years after this, except for a period in the 1980s where the competition was held every three years.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] The ALFC was initially a separate organisation but was absorbed into the AFC in 1986.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] From 1975 to 1981, matches were 60 minutes in duration.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] The competition has been dominated by countries from the Pacific Rim or Eastern Asia (including East and Southeast Asia), with the China women's national football team having won 9 times, including a series of 7 consecutive victories as of 2022 edition.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] Countries from Central and West Asia have been rather less successful, with only Uzbekistan, Kazakhstan, Jordan and Iran having qualified so far.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] Eastern Asia has also been far more frequent in participating in the FIFA Women's World Cup, with five strongest women's teams of Asia (China, North Korea, Japan, Australia, and South Korea) hail from this part.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] The tournament frequency changed to every 4 years effective from 2010, after AFC had announced that the Asian Cup will additionally serve as the qualification rounds of the 2015 FIFA Women's World Cup.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] Until 2003, teams were invited by the AFC to compete.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] From 2006, a separate qualification was established and the number of teams will be decided by the merit by qualification process.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] The name of the tournament was also changed to as the "*AFC Women's Asian Cup*", to reflect the change and reforms of the competition.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] The tournament was expanded from eight teams to twelve starting from the 2022 edition.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] On 20 August 2023, AFC has decided to shift the AFC Women's Asian Cup to non-FIFA Women's World Cup odd years, which will see the edition after the upcoming 2026 AFC Women's Asian Cup takes place in 2029 instead of 2030.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] On 13 September 2024, AFC announced the change in the format of their women's national team competitions, including a new qualifying format for the Women's Asian Cup.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] In addition, the Women's Asian Cup will no longer serve as Asian qualifying tournament for the FIFA Women's World Cup from 2031 and instead serve as qualification for AFC Women's Olympic Qualifying Tournament from 2028.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] The current AFC Women’s Asian Cup trophy was manufactured by London-based company, Thomas Lyte.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] First presented in 2018, the trophy is made from 5.5kg of sterling silver, and sits at 52.5cm in height.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] The six handles represent the six countries which took part in the inaugural competition in 1975.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] The base of the trophy is decorated with the images of eight modern female footballers.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] All of the 47 members of the AFC who have a women's national team are eligible to participate in the qualification tournament.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] Starting from 2022 edition, a total of twelve teams participate in the final tournament including the hosts, top three finishers of the previous edition and eight teams from the qualification tournament.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] In this ranking 3 points are awarded for a win, 1 for a draw and 0 for a loss.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] As per statistical convention in football, matches decided in extra time are counted as wins and losses, while matches decided by penalty shoot-outs are counted as draws.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-asian-cup] Teams are ranked by total points, then by goal difference, then by goals scored.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-futsal-asian-cup] The **AFC Women's Futsal Asian Cup** (previously the **AFC Women's Futsal Championship** before 2021), is the quadrennial premier national women's futsal competition of the Asian Football Confederation nations.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-futsal-asian-cup] The first edition was held in Malaysia in 2015.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-futsal-asian-cup] Starting from 2025, the tournament serves as a qualification for the FIFA Futsal Women's World Cup.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afc-women-s-futsal-asian-cup] Japan are the reigning champions, having won their first title in 2025.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afl-asia-cup] The **AFL Asia Cup** is a triennial international tournament in Australian rules football.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afl-asia-cup] It is the biggest international tournament in the sport that is open to all nations in Asia.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afl-asia-cup] It was created as a replacement of the AFL International Cup alongside the AFL Transatlantic Cup and the AFL Pacific Cup after the competition was affected by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afl-asia-cup] In August 2021, the AFL announced that the IC would return in 2023 to align with its original three-year schedule but did not announce the host.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afl-asia-cup] On 22 April 2022, the AFL announced it was postponing the International Cup until 2024 citing "significant investment required from the AFL to host the event".
[src:afl-asia-cup/afl-asia-cup] However, on 24 July 2023, the AFL announced that, in lieu of the International Cup, that it would be sponsoring three regional events in 2024: the Trans-Atlantic Cup, the Asia Cup, and the Pacific Cup to be hosted by an international affiliate.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afl-asia-cup] The AFL gave no indication as to when the International Cup would be resumed, however indicated that these are the only AFL sanctioned international tournaments since 2017 (effectively nullifying the 2019 and 2022 AFL Europe Championship).
[src:afl-asia-cup/afl-asia-cup] AFL Canada was announced as host of the Transatlantic Cup to be held at the Humber College Oval at Colonel Samuel Smith Park in Toronto on August 2–11, The Maroochydore Multi Sports Complex on the Sunshine Coast, Queensland was announced as the host of the Pacific Cup on 14–24 November.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afl-asia-cup] Thanh Long Sports Center in Vietnam would host the Asia Cup at in Ho Chi Minh City from December 6–8 in 2024.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afl-asia-cup] The AFL announced strict selection criteria, that each player must hold citizenship for the country that they are representing and must have played in from a local competition in that country.
[src:afl-asia-cup/afl-asia-cup] The 2024 competition was contested by 10 teams in the men's division and 4 teams in the women's division.
